results.notes: Datos de Yopal, registrado en Bosque Seco Tropical (temporada de lluvia). Precipitación mínima de 15 – 25 mm en los meses de enero y diciembre, Precipitación máxima 350 mm y 300 mm en los meses de mayo, junio y julio. con menos de 60 mm de lluvia en el mes más seco y precipitación anual superior a 1270 mm. Cuenta con valores mínimos de humedad relativa a inicio del año (65%), y valores más altos en junio, julio, agosto y septiembre (90-85%). cuenta con una altura sobre el nivel del mar entre 0 y 1000 m, una pluviosidad entre 2000 y 4000 mm y temperatura promedio mayor de 24 °C, con amplitud de temperatura máxima de 8 °C, como se referencia en DANE. Los máximos valores de temperatura no sobrepasan los 36 °C y los mínimos valores no logran bajar los 19 °C que se presentan en febrero y en julio, respectivamente. Temperatura media anual mayor de 20 °C, con una estación seca y una lluviosa bien definidas. (Bustamante et al., 2017; DANE, 1999; Castro y Sosa, 2017). Son comunes plantas representativas como Yarumo (Cecropia peltata), Jobo (Spondias mombin), Cedro (Cedrela odorata), Nauno (Albizzia guachepele), Cañafistol (Cassia moschata), Flor blanco (Tabebuia orinocensis), Uña de gato (Cynodon dactylon), entre otras.
results.location_name: Yopal, Casanare, Colombia

results.notes:
Near the riparian zone of the Boise river. These where immediately below russian olive trees, but it was a populus type tree with white bark, in a yard near by.
This observation goes with MO#440507.
These pictures represent the cluster number 3. These were much deeper (maybe because the freezing nights), and they are confusing because the stature is different, and they have traits that they could point to other species like T. pessundatum and T. albobrunneum:
1) Pale faintly grooved margin, dark drop like blotches…
2) Radially fibrillose cap, without dark blotches…
The taste and smell in all of these is farinaceous, not bitter.
The spore size fits better Fungi of Temperate Europe than the local guides, the spores are a little shorter, which makes them more broadly ellipsoid, average (5.08 x3.8) Q=1.33.
The gills are notched and close. Some of the gills have a darker edge, some are pretty white, and in some cases they are interveined, which I can’t find as a described characteristic.

results.notes:
Near the riparian zone of the Boise river. These where immediately below russian olive trees, but it was a populus type tree with white bark, in a yard near by.
This observation goes with MO#440506.
They were 3 clusters of Tricholoma populinum, the closer to the tree were more superficial, and the stems are really bulbous, the medium cluster has a more typical stature, and the furthest cluster was deeper and has really long stipes.
These pictures are for clusters 1 and 2.
The spores are about the same: (4.5-5.6) x (3.6-4.1). These spore sizes fit much better with Fungi of Temperate Europe, that with the local guides.

results.notes: Mixed woods (oaks, pine and palm). Initially it smelled like orange juice to me while my girlfriend thought it smelled pleasant and metallic in some way. Within an hour it became a much less pleasant in a way you’d expect in a older/decayed specimen. Tastewise it was indistinct but left a lingering nutty aftertaste. The bruising is a large part of what’s throwing me off on this one, on the pores I was seeing minor amounts of very quick green blue staining that immediately became brownish red to dark brown, or just straight red brown/brown bruising skipping the bluish phase. On bisection it appeared fully white with a faintly discolored portion in the stipe which became more widely spread and visible becoming pink within 5minutes and roughly an hour later shifting toward brown. The outer stipe skin exhibited red staining as well. I would say the pictures depicting a darker cap skin are more accurate, the ones of it in situ were taken in worse lighting. The pictures showing the development of bruising/staining are timestamped.
